## The files

- **ARCHITECTURE.md** *(agent)* — layers, dependency rules, key invariants/singletons, conventions,
  data flow, storage, known quirks, build/run/test. Read this before touching code.
- **MODULE_MAP.md** *(agent)* — per-file public API (classes, key functions, signatures) so you can
  work without reading every source file.
- **USER_MANUAL.md** *(human)* — domain concepts and end-user behavior. Authoritative on *behavior
  and domain*, not on code structure.
- **CHANGELOG.md** — chronological record of changes (newest first). Archived in chunks once it
  passes 500 lines (see its header).
- **ROADMAP.md** — planned/desired features and the claim convention (set Owner + branch before you
  start) so collaborators don't duplicate work.
- **archive/** — original design briefs/notes (historical; superseded by the live docs where they
  conflict) plus archived `CHANGELOG-archive-NN.md` chunks.

## Maintenance rules

1. **Code change ⇒ doc change in the same pass.** New/renamed public symbol or file → update
   MODULE_MAP; new behavior/quirk/dependency → update ARCHITECTURE; any of the above → add a
   CHANGELOG entry (newest first).
2. **Keep the agent docs terse and accurate.** They exist to save reading the whole project; stale
   entries are worse than none. Prefer fixing an existing line over appending duplicates.
3. **Don't edit archived documents** — they are a historical snapshot. Capture corrections in the
   live docs.
4. **USER_MANUAL is the domain source of truth**; ARCHITECTURE/MODULE_MAP are the code source of truth.
5. **CHANGELOG stays under 500 lines** — archive older entries per its header rule (move, never delete).
6. **Claim roadmap items before starting** (Owner + branch in ROADMAP.md, committed first) and retire
   them to CHANGELOG when shipped.
